@{u}Auto-handling@{uu}

The aim of this mode is to allow the user to make a mistake...

Under Intuition, when you click on a gadget, it is pushed and remain pushed
while you keep the mouse button pressed. Futhermore if you move the mouse
out of the button while continuing to press the mouse button, the gadget
come back to its initial state. At last if the mouse is removed under the
button, it is repushed.

In order to manage your buttons this way in AMOS, it's quite difficult, even
using the POWER Procedures. However the new auto-handling mode available for
nearly all the gadgets handles this auto-magically and returns only if the
button was eventualy pressed or not by the user. If it's a palette gadget
(@{"PW_COLOR" LINK "PW_COLOR"}) then the procedure returns the color selected
, idem for the radios buttons, ...

For you the only thing to do is to redefine a zone around the gadget, which
is quite easy with the global variables PW_XMIN, PW_YMIN, PW_XMAX, PW_YMAX,
then to call the procedure in the auto-handling mode when the user `start'
clicking on the gadget.
 
This mode is even available for the keyboard. The principle is slightly dif-
ferent : when the user press a defined key (put in the global variable PW_KEY)
the button is pushed and stay pushed while the key is pressed. However, if
the space bar is pressed simultanately, the button is unpushed.


@{u}Multi-string / Sub-string@{uu}

A multi-string is a simple string but containing some `|' characters delimi-
ting a certain number of sub-string.

    ex : A$="String 1|String 2|...|String N"

In order to recover the sub-strings, you can use the PW_PARSE procedure.


@{u}Global and local variables@{uu}

All the variables declared within a procedure work separately from the other
variables of your program. These variables are called local variables.

All the external  variables to the  procedures are  called global variables,
and are not affected by the operations within a procedure.

The `Shared' instruction permit to transform local variables of one procedu-
re into global variables.

The `Global' instruction permit to make some variables accessible everywhere
in your program, procedures included.
@ENDNODE


